        <h2 id="examples">Real marketing automation examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — Dental practice: new patient booking workflow</h3>
        <p>A dental practice offers a "New Patient Guide" download on their website. The download triggers a 5-email nurture sequence over 14 days — each email covers a different concern (cost, insurance, anxiety, what to expect). The sequence converts website visitors into 15 new monthly bookings without any front desk outreach. Setup time: 8 hours. Monthly revenue impact: 15 patients at average $300 first visit = $4,500/month.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — B2B consulting: LinkedIn-to-email nurture</h3>
        <p>A consulting firm runs LinkedIn ads that drive leads to a landing page. Every form submission triggers a 3-week email sequence that delivers case studies, frameworks, and a case for the firm's methodology. The automated sequence doubled the MQL-to-meeting conversion rate compared to immediate cold outreach, because it warmed leads before asking for calendar time.</p>

        <h3>Example 3 — Ecommerce: abandoned cart recovery</h3>
        <p>An ecommerce brand runs three abandoned cart emails: at 2 hours (reminder), 24 hours (social proof — "4,200 people bought this"), and 72 hours (10% off expiring offer). The sequence recovers 12% of abandoned carts, generating approximately $8,000/month in otherwise-lost revenue on autopilot.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Marketing automation vs. email marketing — which to use</h2>
        <p>Email marketing is a subset of what marketing automation covers. The distinction matters when choosing tools and setting expectations.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Marketing automation</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Spans email, SMS, social, ads, in-app</li>
              <li>Behaviour-triggered workflows</li>
              <li>Dynamic personalisation by segment and action</li>
              <li>Lead scoring and CRM integration</li>
              <li>Attribution across multiple touchpoints</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
