              <li>Email channel only</li>
              <li>Scheduled broadcast campaigns</li>
              <li>List-based segmentation</li>
              <li>Basic list management</li>
              <li>Open and click rate reporting</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 marketing automation best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start with one high-impact workflow.</strong> Pick the workflow with the highest volume and clearest conversion event — usually a lead nurture sequence or abandoned cart. Get that working perfectly before building 20 others that are mediocre.</li>
          <li><strong>Segment from day one.</strong> Even basic segmentation — new vs. returning, by product interest, by traffic source — dramatically improves relevance. The marginal effort is low; the conversion lift is significant.</li>
          <li><strong>Align sales and marketing on lead scoring before you automate it.</strong> If sales considers a lead qualified at score 80 but marketing hands off at score 50, you are automating friction, not removing it.</li>
          <li><strong>Clean your data quarterly.</strong> Automation amplifies data quality — accurate data produces precise personalisation, dirty data produces awkward "Hi [FIRST_NAME]" moments at scale.</li>
          <li><strong>Write emails for one person, not a list.</strong> Automation sends to thousands but each recipient reads it alone. Use "you" throughout, refer to specific actions they took, and write in a conversational tone — not corporate broadcast voice.</li>
          <li><strong>Set re-engagement triggers before you need them.</strong> Build an automatic win-back sequence for contacts who have not engaged in 90 days. Proactive re-engagement is cheaper than acquiring new leads and often recovers 10–15% of inactive contacts.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — automating a broken strategy</div>
          <p>The most expensive marketing automation mistake is using it to scale a marketing approach that was not working manually. Automation does not fix a weak value proposition, irrelevant content, or misaligned targeting — it makes those problems reach more people faster. Validate your messaging and funnel manually first. Then automate what works.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common marketing automation mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Over-automating too early</strong> — building 30 workflows before the first one is proven dilutes focus and creates a maintenance burden.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring unsubscribes and complaints</strong> — automation that sends to unengaged contacts at volume damages deliverability. Remove unengaged contacts before automated campaigns, not after.</li>
          <li><strong>No human review loop</strong> — even automated sequences need quarterly review. Markets change, offers expire, and workflows built 12 months ago often no longer match current positioning.</li>
          <li><strong>Single-channel automation called "omnichannel"</strong> — automating only email and calling it omnichannel is a mismatch. True automation connects email, ads retargeting, CRM alerts, and SMS in one coordinated experience.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping testing</strong> — A/B test subject lines, send times, and CTAs even in automated sequences. A 10% improvement in a workflow that fires 500 times/month compounds significantly.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
